    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-01-05T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-01-05T17:00:00-05:00" n="299"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d299">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.7445/43: Airgram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Officer in Charge at New Delhi</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Merrell</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-01-05T18:00:00-04:00"
                            >January 5, 1944—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>A–8. On February 11, 1943 Board of War Communications approved the shipment of
                    two transmitters from the United States under Lend-Lease<note n="12"
                        xml:id="d299fn12">Lend-Lease Act approved March 11, 1941; 55 Stat.
                        31.</note> to India for the establishment of direct radio telegraph circuits
                    between the United States and India<note n="13" xml:id="d299fn13">The view of
                        the Board was that in the interest of national security duplicate circuits
                        should be established between the United States and Bombay
                        (811.7445/–51).</note> with the understanding that delivery would be made in
                    June 1943. The Board has received information from the British Ministry of
                    Supply that the two transmitters manufactured by KCA Manufacturing Company
                    should arrive in India about January 15, 1944 and be ready for service in the
                    latter part of February 1944. See your 952, December 14, 5 p.m.<note n="14"
                        xml:id="d299fn14">Not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
